_source.doc_summary: This document is a comprehensive report on the South of Embley Pre-feasibility Study Project Development. It details the proposed mining operations south of the Embley River, including the expansion of existing operations at East Weipa and Andoom, and the development of a new operation at South of Embley (SoE). The report outlines the operating costs, closure costs, port charges, and feasibility study costs. It also discusses the COMET Optimisation Model used for business analysis, the expansion proposal, risk assessment, operating authorities, environmental assessments, and sustainable development criteria. The document emphasizes the potential benefits and risks associated with the project, along with the necessary approvals and legal considerations.

1. Social - Enhance human potential and well- being	Status
1.1 Does the action affect the safety and health of employees, neighbours, customers, or final consumers?	There are potential occupational health and safety impacts on employees that exist as part of the current Weipa operation (e.g. operating in or adjacent heavy mobile equipment and fixed plant). The SoE mine will be situated on land of the traditional owners from Aurukun. The majority of these people will be unfamiliar with the mining operation. Access to identified significant sites on the mine lease must be maintained, and the infrastructure layout is cognisant of this, by incorporating the following; - Initial plant facilities are centralised in a single location that will be fenced and includes security access - Selected route for the connecting road between Hey Pt & Boyd Pt mine facilities minimises short to medium term civil / haul road crossings.
1.2 Does the action affect the quality of life of relevant stakeholders (economic enhancement, cultural heritage, social cohesion, workplace diversity, etc.)?	Improved quality of life can be expected for many locally engaged operations personnel, as workplace HSE standards are likely to be at the high quality end of the range on offer. The project is likely to be economically positive for most stakeholders, in the existing Weipa & Napranum communities and provide better opportunities for the Aurukun community. Although the SoE mine facilities are further from the Mapoon communities than the existing mine centres, this is not expected to impact on these communities quality of life. Employees from these communities reside in Weipa. Identification of significant sites & effect on plant layout to accommodate safe access will be undertaken as part of the feasibility study. A cultural heritage management process is in place with Traditional Owners. Significant Cultural heritage sites to be identified and not disturbed.

_source.doc_summary: This document is a pre-feasibility study for the development of the South of Embley ore body, focusing on the optimal timing and size for its development. It summarizes the current ore body knowledge, depletion sequence, mining method, operating strategy, and capital development estimates. The study also includes an analysis of previous studies, key inputs from a May 2006 workshop, and Weipa's forecasted annual production. The document outlines the scope of the pre-feasibility study, including the preparation of an operating strategy, engineering solution, cost estimates, and a project business model. It details capital and operating cost modelling, closure costs, and the feasibility study cost estimate. The study concludes that the development of the South of Embley ore body adds value to the business and recommends the commencement of an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) and feasibility study.

_source.doc_summary: This document is a pre-feasibility study report for the South of Embley (SoE) mining project, detailing the business model, options analysis, and environmental considerations. The COMET Optimisation Model was used to evaluate expansion options for existing operations at East Weipa and Andoom, as well as the potential for new operations south of the Embley River. The report outlines various expansion scenarios, their financial implications, and the environmental impact assessments. It also discusses the necessary statutory approvals, water rights, and sustainable development criteria. The project aims to optimize economic contribution while minimizing environmental damage and enhancing social well-being.
_source.text: The WCCCA consultation group has been notified that RTA are conducting preliminary environmental investigations within the South of Embley area, with the aspiration to commence an EIS sometime during 2008. The WCCCA consultation group will be involved with the EIS process and will have the opportunity to review formal environmental applications prior to submission. Regular updates on the feasibility study progress will be provided to the WCCCA consultation group.
